# Data Card — {{PROJECT_NAME}}

A people-centered transparency summary of this project's dataset, in the spirit of the [Data Cards Playbook](https://sites.research.google/datacardsplaybook/) — a right-sized subset of its 15 documentation dimensions. It documents the facts a reader needs to decide whether and how to (re)use the data. This complements — it does not replace — the field-level schema in `DATA-DICTIONARY.md`. Right-size it: fill the themes that matter for this dataset and leave the rest. Where useful, answer at more than one depth — a short overview, a concrete example, then a fuller explanation.

## Overview

- **Dataset:** `<dataset name>` · version `<version>` · last updated {{YEAR}}.
- **Summary:** one or two sentences on what this dataset is and who it serves.
- **Sensitivity:** {{SENSITIVITY_TIER}}. **Openness:** {{OPENNESS}}. **License:** {{LICENSE}}.
- **Maintainer:** {{PI_NAME}} · {{CONTACT_EMAIL}} · {{LAB_NAME}}.
- **Authorship:** who created and who owns the dataset; funding sources.

## Motivation & intended use

Why this dataset exists, who it is for (design partners and beneficiaries), and the questions it is meant to support. State what the data can plausibly support — description and comparison far more readily than prediction.

## Provenance & collection

Upstream sources and their licenses; how and when the data was collected or annotated, and by whom; the chain of custody. Note whether the source is reachable and re-released. (Detailed field provenance lives in `DATA-DICTIONARY.md`.)

## Composition

What the dataset contains: the unit of observation (grain), approximate size, the tables/files, and how they relate. Note major transformations applied, how any labels or annotations were produced, the sampling method, and how the data was validated. Point to `DATA-DICTIONARY.md` for the field-level schema rather than duplicating it here.

## Recommended & out-of-scope uses

The uses this dataset is suitable for, and — just as important — the uses it is **not** suitable for. Naming foreseeable misuses up front is part of responsible release.

<!-- IF:SENSITIVE -->## Sensitive attributes & fairness

This dataset is **{{SENSITIVITY_TIER}}**. Identify PII and protected/sensitive attributes; representation and sampling gaps; known or suspected biases; and the populations who could be harmed by misuse or re-identification. Pair any identifier/retention affordance with the access tiers and remedy process recorded in `GOVERNANCE.md` (or, until that exists, in `ROADMAP.md`) — affordances without duties are theater. Complete the `responsible-data-checklist` before ingesting or sharing.<!-- /IF -->

## Known limitations & caveats

The data problems found and how they were handled (missing values, inconsistent encodings, suspicious sentinels, truncation, totals that don't reconcile), and the limitations that constrain use. Mirror the entries in `DATA-DICTIONARY.md`'s "Known issues" and any `data-quality-checklist`.

## Maintenance & governance

Who maintains the dataset, the update cadence, how to report a problem, access conditions, the retention schedule, the disposal/wipeout plan, and what survives the pilot (named custodians). Link `GOVERNANCE.md` and `decision-log.md` where present.

